ğŸ§  1. What is Windows PowerShell?
PowerShell is a task-based command-line shell and scripting language built on .NET. It's designed for system administration and automating tasks.

Combines the power of Unix-like shells with scripting capabilities.

Works with cmdlets â€“ small .NET-based commands.

Example:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Process
ğŸ›ï¸ 2. Windows PowerShell Architecture
PowerShell has four key components:

Hosting Layer â€“ Runs in consoles, ISE, Visual Studio Code, etc.

Engine â€“ Handles parsing, pipeline processing, execution.

Cmdlets & Providers â€“ Interact with data sources like file systems, registry.

.NET Runtime â€“ Executes the compiled code.

ğŸ”§ 3. Understanding the Commands
Cmdlets are in Verb-Noun format.

You can use Get-Command to list available commands.

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Command
ğŸ§¾ 4. Identifying the Parameters
Use Get-Help to learn about command parameters.

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Help Get-Process -Full
Try tab-completion to explore parameters:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Service -Name <TAB>
ğŸ”— 5. Working with the Pipeline
The pipeline (|) passes output from one command to another.

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Process | Where-Object {$_.CPU -gt 10}
ğŸ“¤ 6. Exporting, Importing, and Converting Data
Export to CSV/JSON/XML:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Process | Export-Csv process.csv
Import:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Import-Csv process.csv
Convert:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Service | ConvertTo-Json
ğŸš¿ 7. Filtering Objects Out of the Pipeline
Use Where-Object and Select-Object.

powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Process | Where-Object { $_.WorkingSet -gt 50000000 } | Select-Object Name, ID
ğŸ¨ 8. Formatting Output
powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Process | Format-Table Name, ID, CPU
Get-Service | Format-List
ğŸ“ 9. Redirecting Formatted Output
powershell
Copy
Edit
Get-Process | Out-File "processes.txt"
Get-Process | Out-Printer
ğŸ“¦ 10. Creating Your Own Module
Create a .psm1 file:

powershell
Copy
Edit
function Hello-User { param($Name) "Hello $Name" }
Save as MyModule.psm1

Use:

powershell
Copy
Edit
Import-Module .\MyModule.psm1
Hello-User -Name "Alex"
